(xii)  conduct a required feature of RAMIS for future inclusion of digital signatures; and 
(xiii)  guide the DRC in data preparation and data entry. 

4.  Business process engineering analyst (international, 3 person-months). The analyst 
will have at least 7 years of experience in process studies, reengineering, and redesign in the 
context of IT enablement of the business processes of an organization. The analyst must have 
been  associated  with  reengineering  of  business  processes  in  government  administration, 
preferably in tax and revenue administration. The analyst will have at least a master’s degree in 
business administration or a relevant discipline. The analyst will perform the following tasks: 
(i)  lead the as-is business process study, and conduct the issues analysis and to-be 
business process study; 
(ii)  lead efforts for business process reengineering for functions of the DRC; 
(iii)  conduct a best practices study in tax administration and recommend adoption of 
relevant best practices for the DRC; 
(iv)  define to-be processes for the DRC, including identification of IT enablement 
opportunities, through consultation with the team leader; 
(v)  define functional requirement specifications for RAMIS;  
(vi)  assess the impact of changes in the current business processes on the existing 
regulatory framework guiding the DRC; and 
(vii)  provide dedicated training in coordination with the team leader and the capacity-
building expert. 

5.  System engineering and IT security specialist (international, 3 person-months). The 
specialist will have at least 7 years of experience in design and engineering of IT applications 
and software systems for organizations with a large user base and multiple locations. The 
specialist will have at least a master’s degree in IT or computer science, or a relevant discipline. 
The specialist will perform the following tasks: 
(i)  assist in conducting the as-is study and functionality analysis for introducing an 
internally acceptable e-tax filing system;  
(ii)  prepare the system requirement specification and system design document in 
consultation with the team leader; 
(iii)  provide inputs for developing the architecture definition and design for the e-tax 
filing system from a network perspective, especially keeping in mind that the 
application will be used over a wide area network and the internet;  
(iv)  identify software and tools required for the design and implementation of RAMIS; 
(v)  conduct a study of commercially available off-the-shelf products;  
(vi)  customize application software for RAMIS and test the application software;  
(vii)  provide advice for timely resolution of all technical issues;  
(viii)  assess the information security risk for RAMIS and identify potential security 
threats to the system, from both internal and external users; 
(ix)  identify  suitable  information  security  measures  and  solutions  to  address  the 
identified risks; 
(x)  design the security management, framework, and architecture for RAMIS; 
(xi)  configure and implement information security solutions;

