(ii)  assess the IT infrastructure requirement for procurement and implementation as 
needed for the e-tax filing system, if necessary; 
(iii)  prepare the bill of material for the IT infrastructure procurement required for the 
e-tax filing system; 
(iv)  conduct analysis of network architecture requirements and IT infrastructure sizing;  
(v)  assist the DRC in finalizing the IT infrastructure requirements and procurement; 
(vi)  assist in creating a business continuity plan for RAMIS; 
(vii)  prepare an analysis report on the tax identification system, and potential system 
interfacing and integration between the e-tax system and the customs system;  
(viii)  conduct training and public awareness programs in consultation with the DRC 
and the consulting firm; and 
(ix)  install and operationalize the IT infrastructure for RAMIS. 

10.  National System developers (two nationals, 16 person-months; 8 person-months each). 
The developers will have at least 3 years of experience in designing software systems on the 
development platform proposed for RAMIS development and implementation. The developers 
will have at least a bachelor’s degree in IT or computer science, or a relevant discipline. The 
recruitment will require the consultation with the Government. The developers will perform the 
following tasks: 
(i)  conduct a requirements study and documentation; 
(ii)  prepare software requirement specifications; 
(iii)  develop  application  software  under  the  guidance  of  the  system  developer 
(international consultant); 
(iv)  prepare documentation for the software;  
(v)  conduct unit testing of the software and provide user support and troubleshooting; 
(vi)  implement RAMIS and train the users; 
(vii)  support  international  consultants  in  undertaking  research,  data  collation,  and 
analysis to enable the completion of the envisaged tasks within the stipulated 
time frames; and  
(viii)  provide support for conducting workshops and focus group meetings. 

B.  Individual Consultant 

11.  Revenue policies and regulatory expert (international, 2 person-months). The expert 
will have at least 10 years of experience in the development of revenue systems, revenue-
related policies and procedures, and regulatory frameworks. The expert will have at least a 
master’s degree in IT or computer science, or a relevant discipline. The expert will perform the 
following tasks: 
(i)  conduct  a  review  of  current  tax  and  nontax  revenue,  and  recommend  new 
revenue to be introduced; 
(ii)  conduct a review of the existing legal and regulatory framework relating to the 
revenue  system  and  recommend  a  streamlined  approach  for  revenue 
administration; 
(iii)  develop a road map for the DRC with a detailed plan to enhance the revenue 
system generally and revenue-enhancing strategies and procedures for the 
government; 
(iv)  conduct training and public awareness programs in consultation with the DRC 
and the consulting firm; 
(v)  prepare a report capturing findings and recommendations to be presented during 
workshops; and 
(vi)  conduct other activities requested by ADB relating to implementation of the TA.
